<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 92 / The UK Economy: PSBR exceeds forecasts by Pounds 1bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT borrowing last month came to Pounds 4bn, roughly Pounds 1bn
higher than expected, as the recession cut tax income and pushed up spending
in areas such as social security payments.
The public sector borrowing requirement for the first six months of the
current financial year came to Pounds 18.4bn compared with Pounds 10.8bn in
the corresponding period last year.
Excluding privatisation proceeds of Pounds 1.4bn, the PSBR for the month
came to Pounds 5.4bn, one of the biggest monthly totals on record. The
privatisation receipts came from part-payment investors who have taken a
stake in the regional electricity companies.
News of the worsening state of public finances underlines the probability
that the 1992-93 PSBR will exceed the Treasury's forecast of Pounds 28bn.
Many City economists think the figure will turn out at between Pounds 32bn
and Pounds 35bn.
Total cash outlays by central government departments last month totalled
Pounds 19.5bn, compared with Pounds 19.3bn in August and Pounds 17.9bn in
September 1991.
Over the first six months of the financial year which started in April, the
spending total came to Pounds 114.3bn. This figure, which is arrived at
after subtracting privatisation payments, is 8 per cent more than the Pounds
105.5bn total for the corresponding period last year.
</TEXT>
