<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 92 / Gardening: Plant of the Week - Rosa moyesii
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARTHUR HELLYER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is one of the finest roses to grow for fruits or hips, which are long,
flask-shaped and shining red. It is one of the wild roses of China and
several variations of it exist. Probably the best for garden planting is
called Geranium but the single flowers of this have not got the magnificent
blood red of the wild plant; instead they are geranium red.
The stems are stout, heavily armed with thorns and can grow 10 ft high but
can be kept lower by pruning. The variety geranium is about half this
height. All kinds are completely hardy, will grow in any fertile soil and
need little pruning beyond removal of damaged, diseased or worn out stems in
winter.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
