<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 92 / Census shows fall in London population
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POPULATION of London and the six metropolitan counties fell between 1981
and 1991, according to provisional census results published yesterday by the
Office of Populations Censuses and Surveys.
The estimates from last year's census, however, show that the changes were
generally small - with Merseyside falling the most at 5 per cent - and the
inner London boroughs registered a slight increase.
Outside the cities, all but three shire counties increased in population.
Cambridgeshire, Buckinghamshire, Cornwall and Dorset were the
fastest-growing counties in England and Wales.
Overall, the resident population of England and Wales rose by 1.32m to
50.95m. Two thirds of this was caused by the excess of births over deaths
and the remainder by net immigration. There was a surge in the very youngest
and the oldest: the number of pre-school children rose 422,000 (14 per
cent); and there was an increase of 507,000 (6 per cent) in the number of
people over the retirement ages of 65 for men and 60 for women.
Provisional Mid 1991 Population Estimates for England and Wales. OPCS.
Pounds 2.50.
</TEXT>
