<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 92 / Ukraine holds arms export talks with India
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UKRAINE is negotiating a big arms export deal with India which could include
warships as well as spare parts for Soviet-supplied tanks and aircraft.
India, whose fleet includes modern destroyers made at the Nikolayev yards in
Ukraine, has expressed interest in additional naval vessels including
aircraft carriers, according to officials from the two countries. It
currently has two aircraft carriers bought second-hand from Britain.
It is also seeking spares for its modern T-72 tanks and earlier T-55 models,
as well as for its medium-range Antonov An-32 transport aircraft. India
previously bought most of its arms from the Soviet Union.
Mr Sharad Pawar, the Indian minister of defence, was scheduled today to
conclude a visit to Ukraine, where many of the factories and shipyards which
supply those weapons are located. The deal under discussion is expected to
be based largely on barter.
'It has been agreed by both sides that Ukraine will not have any problem
supplying the spare parts,' the Indian embassy said.
Mr Viktor Antonov, Ukraine's armaments minister, said his country's chief
aim was to replace the old Soviet-Indian contract with a direct bilateral
agreement or even three-way arrangements involving Russia as well.
He complained that payment for the An-32s - produced in Ukraine and supplied
to India in the dying days of the Soviet Union - was going to Russia.
'Our factories will not work for free,' Mr Antonov said. 'That is why, as an
independent state, we would like to conclude bilateral agreements.'
Indian trade with the former Soviet Union was facilitated by a rouble-rupee
clearing arrangement. That has now fallen apart and Mr Antonov said it was
difficult to find an alternative.
The Indian deal points to the emergence of Ukraine as an important
international arms supplier. Ukrainian officials denied suggestions this
year that the country paid for 5m tonnes of Iranian oil with weapons.
</TEXT>
