<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 92 / Nigerian leader cracks down on political parties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NIGERIA'S transition to civilian rule suffered a serious setback yesterday
when the military government nullified the results of last month's
presidential primaries and dissolved the executives of the country's two
political parties.
The decision, prompted by widespread electoral fraud, seems likely to
disrupt the transition timetable which envisaged presidential elections in
December, and a formal handover by President Ibrahim Babangida in early
January.
General Babangida, who seized power in a 1985 coup, took the decision after
a meeting of the Armed Forces Ruling Council (AFRC) had reviewed a report of
the National Electoral Commission.
After an AFRC meeting in Abuja, the Nigerian capital, Gen Babangida said
that caretaker committees would take over administration of the Social
Democratic party (SDP) and the National Republican Convention (NRC), while
the electoral commission would draw up new guidelines for the selection of
party candidates.
The AFRC was 'firmly committed to bringing about a viable democracy at all
levels of government in accordance with electoral laws,' Gen Babangida said.
Although most observers agree that electoral fraud discredited the
primaries, the transition process was fundamentally flawed from the start.
In 1987, in the early stages of the programme, thousands of former
politicians and government officials were banned from politics in an
ineffectual attempt to create a 'new breed' of leaders. Two years later the
government presided over the creation of the SDP and the NRC, whose
near-identical manifestos were drawn up by civil servants.
The credibility of the process suffered a further blow when the government
insisted the only way to prevent electoral fraud was to use the open-ballot
system, under which voters line up for counting in front of a poster of
their favoured candidate.
But faced with a choice between taking part in a flawed transition to
democracy or resigning themselves to military rule, many Nigerians
reluctantly opted for the former.
Should Gen Babangida delay the handover there is likely to be widespread
resentment among a civilian population increasingly critical of the
military's mismanagement and government corruption.
</TEXT>
