<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 92 / Noises on and noises off: Jurek Martin reflects from the
serenity of Sanibel, deep down Florida's Gulf coast, on this week's ructions
in Washington
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WASHINGTON is the best of towns and it is the worst of towns. No town
contains a greater distillation of political sophistication and no town can
be as divorced from political reality. This week demonstrated the ultimate
contrast.
All the noises in Washington are of men at war and jumping ship. If, as is
still more likely than not, the effective administration of President George
Bush has only 2 1/2 more weeks to run, its final days are not exactly filled
with sweetness and light.
But, here in the hinterland, if the questions posed by Joe and Mary Public
to Messrs Bush, Clinton and Perot in Richmond, Virginia, on Thursday are any
guide, these noises might as well be on Mars. That does not make them less
sonorous, or less important, but it does put them into perspective.
The Washington ear is tuned into the fascinating fact that the Justice
Department is investigating the Federal Bureau of Investigation, which is in
turn investigating the Justice Department, of which the FBI is
institutionally a part. The Central Intelligence Agency is also trading
allegations with the Justice Department. All the fusillades have their
origins in the Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL) affair.
Similarly, Budget Director Richard Darman has done his best to blame
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and Mr Michael Boskin, chairman of the
council of economic advisers, for making a mess of the president's tax
policies, They have been a bit too polite to respond, but all has been
revealed in exquisite detail by Bob Woodward in the Washington Post.
Over at the State Department, now free of the hegemony of Mr James Baker,
who is occupied with running President Bush's re-election campaign,
officials are speaking with delicious indiscretion over the circumstances of
the departmental investigation of presidential challenger Bill Clinton's
private life. That the investigation should have been overseen by an
unpopular political appointee named to her post at the behest of Mr John
Sununu, the former White House chief of staff whom all Washington loves to
hate now that he is out, is merely an explanation.
Nobody, it seems, had the will to restore order. Not Mr Baker, whose
long-awaited speech - either on the economy or on why he thinks Mr Bush
should be re-elected - remained undelivered.
Not Mr William Sessions, director of the FBI, now under fire for having
dodged taxes, billing the government for private phone calls and other
hanging offences.
Not CIA chief Robert Gates, who is in Russia, presumably looking for
evidence that the KGB planted a transmitter in Mr Clinton's lower lip 23
years ago in Moscow.
Nor - apart from Arabs buying US, not British, tanks as if they were going
out of style - was there much evidence of foreigners jumping on board Mr
Bush's ship. Most German chancellors, including socialists, endorse
Republican presidents but, consumed by Eurodramas and a few local
difficulties, Helmut Kohl has said not a word.
Nor has British Prime Minister John Major displayed any public gratitude for
the wholescale lifting by the Republicans of last spring's Tory campaign.
Even the Japanese, who tend to respond automatically to requests from the
White House, have been quiet, privately concentrating on working out what Mr
Clinton's trade policies really are. French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas
stands alone in his endorsement, and that was delivered months ago.
The curious thing is that, throughout all this, Mr Bush has remained almost
serene. He has a pit bull terrier for vice-president and assorted
rottweilers called Matalin, Fitzwater and Dornan, but the president himself
often seems as passive as his family dog, Millie.
Mr Bush does get rattled occasionally and still misspeaks himself but,
mostly, he stands on the dignity of being president. He applauded Mr Quayle
for the savagery of his debate onslaught this week, but having been set up
by Mr Quayle for the Thursday round, he barely raised his voice.
Though Mr Quayle would have taken any opportunity to impugn Mr Clinton, Mr
Bush did not. He answered the questions put to him, less well than Mr
Clinton and less entertainingly than Mr Perot, but he answered them.
Only once in 90 minutes were there even allusions to Vietnam, Moscow, trust,
character or all the other things that Washington thinks he must make stick
in order to retain the presidency. On the other side, yet again the names of
Iran and Iraq, let alone a certain subsidiary of an Italian bank, never
crossed a questioner's lips.
The Washington conclusion is there is no iron in Mr Bush's soul. The country
may well also be about to vote him out, but not because he lacks iron or any
other vitamin that might transform him into the Man Who Eats Democrats For
Breakfast. It is because he has run out of ideas on the real problems of
real people. He ought to be here; at least the tide comes in and out.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-13105</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJRAMAALFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921017
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 OCT 92 / Rate cut fails to calm coal storm: Major faces toughest
crisis as Tory MPs threaten Commons revolt over pit closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR was strug-gling last night to weather the most severe crisis
of his premiership after a 1 percentage point cut in interest rates to 8 per
cent failed to calm the storm of protest against British Coal's drastic pit
closure plan.
With Conservative MPs threatening defeat for the government on the closures
when the House of Commons returns next week, the prime minister offered a
second olive branch to his critics by promising training for the 31,000
miners facing unemployment.
The training measures, which will be detailed in the Commons on Monday by Mr
Michael Hesel-tine, trade and industry secretary, will be channelled through
employer-led Training and Enterprise Councils.
Mr Major acknowledged also the growing concern among industrialists that the
economic recession now threatens to turn into a slump. He promised an
intensive dialogue between Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, and business
leaders to explore how the government could help industry to take advantage
of the competitive edge provided by the devaluation of the pound.
In a stark warning of the task the government faces to head off a revolt in
Wednesday's coal debate, Sir Marcus Fox, a barometer of backbench opinion in
his role as chairman of the 1922 committee of Conservative MPs, had earlier
said the plan's scale was 'unacceptable' and had 'incensed' colleagues.
With their anxieties over the economy only partly relieved by the rate cut,
the number of Tory MPs publicly questioning the coal proposals easily
exceeds the 11 needed to overturn the government's Commons majority of 21 -
and some rebels were predicting victory.
A Yorkshire Post survey last night found 44 out of the 72 Tory MPs who
responded said they did not support the government's handling of the pit
closures.
Speaking at the end of the European Community summit in Birmingham, Mr Major
insisted that there could be no going back on the decision to close 31 of
British Coal's 50 pits.
He acknowledged the 'an-guish' which had been caused by the scale and speed
of the programme. But insisting there was no prospect of finding a market
for the stockpiles of coal building up at pitheads and generating stations,
he added: 'The fact was that we simply could not ignore reality.' Financing
the surplus production was costing the government Pounds 100m a month.
He said the announcement had come after a detailed analysis of both the UK's
strategic energy needs and of whether some of the 'marginal pits' could
survive.
Mr Heseltine will face the 1922 committee before Wednesday's debate in what
could be a stormy confrontation.
Labour plans to introduce a motion to attract maximum Tory support. 'We will
be doing everything possible for those Tory MPs who believe that the
government has got it wrong to record that view on Wednesday,' said Mr Robin
Cook, the party's trade and industry spokesman.
Labour and the Liberal Democrats have launched national campaigns to save
pits. Mr John Smith, Labour leader, said the prime minister had ordered 'a
panic interest rate cut and a panic announcement of extra assistance for
sacked miners'.
The crisis of confidence over the handling of the decision to shut 31 of
British Coal's 50 pits ahead of privatisation overshadowed the EC summit.
Downing Street added to the confusion by issuing a third version of which
cabinet members had been told in advance of the closures announcement.
Betraying the apparent haste with which the plans were drawn up and agreed,
Mr David Hunt, Welsh secretary, said he had been 'surprised' by British
Coal's decision to close the Point of Ayr pit in Wales. He has asked for
clarification and further information from the company.
Mr Major said the interest rate cut was fully justified in terms of the
government's commitment to bring down inflation. But his emphasis on his
concern to help 'families and industry' was an acknowledgement of the damage
done by the closures announcement.
Despite the Treasury's justification of the rate cut, there was suspicion
that its timing had been dictated by the mounting political crisis.
Tory backbenchers publicly welcomed the move but it failed to stop private
anxieties of many over the lack of a clear economic strategy since the UK's
withdrawal from the European exchange rate mechanism.
Major abandons policy for crisis management; Lenders make cautious
start, Page 8
