<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Russia to adopt mineral
licensing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA IS about to finalise a licensing system for the exploitation of both
new and old deposits of its mineral wealth in an important step towards
building a market system.
Mr Viktor Orlov, head of the state geology committee, said yesterday that
the state had already begun to collect royalties last month on the basis of
temporary instructions. It is these instructions, issued to give substance
to an earlier law on mineral deposits, which will be made permanent by a
government decision expected within days.
After decades of waste and abuse resulting from an absence of licensing
arrangements, which are common in the capitalist world, the Russian
royalties will have to be paid by both foreign and Russian enterprises.
The licences will also set clear terms for the use of resources to cut down
on waste and environmental damage which is so rife of the oil gas and mining
sectors. If the Russian authorities are able to enforce licensing
conditions, the new system may also help cut down on corruption.
Mr Orlov said the royalty rates levied since September as a percentage of
the value of what is produced included: 8 per cent for oil, gas and coal,
2.4-4 per cent for strategic metals, up to 10 per cent for gold, and 5 per
cent for diamonds and precious stones. These could be adjusted upwards or
downwards for depreciation and other factors, and rates for existing
deposits may be changed in the government's final document. Royalties for
new deposits will be determined by tendering authorities.
Chevron, the US oil company, and the former Soviet republic of Kazakhstan
have agreed to go ahead from January 1, 1993, with a 50:50 joint venture to
exploit the huge Tengiz oil field, Russian news agencies said yesterday,
reports Reuter from Moscow.
Industry analysts say Tengiz is regarded as one of the world's top ten
fields with probable reserves up to 35bn barrels. Current output is just
60,000 barrels a day.
Chevron clinched a deal to help increase the volume in May and Itar-Tass
news agency said details had now been firmed up during a visit by Chevron
chief Mr Kenneth Derr, when he met Mr Nursultan Nazarbayev, the Kazakh
president.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 32
</PAGE>
