<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Finnish banks incur FM6bn loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HELSINKI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE CRISIS in Finland's financial sector deepened yesterday after three of
the country's leading banks announced losses of more than FM6bn (Pounds
759m) for the first eight months.
The scale of the losses forced the government to reiterate its support for
the sector as it warned that billions more markka in new state grants would
be needed next year.
Three of the leading banks, Unitas (the holding company for the Union Bank
of Finland), Skopbank and Kansallis-Osaki-Pankki (KOP), warned that their
performance was unlikely to improve in the final four months, with total
losses for the year likely to exceed FM9bn.
The banks have been battered by the severe Finnish recession and the high
level of real interest rates. Credit losses and non-performing loans have
soared. Rising funding costs, stagnant credit demand and falling share
prices have added to difficulties.
The most severe problems are being encountered by small and medium-sized
businesses, many of which have been forced into bankruptcy, but the personal
sector has not escaped the ravages caused by a 13 per cent unemployment
rate. Total credit write-offs announced by the three banks for the first
eight months amounted to FM5.2bn.
The problems mean that Unitas, the holding company for the Union Bank of
Finland, will now seek FM1.75bn in preference capital from the government,
the maximum possible sum allowed under a FM8bn scheme set up earlier this
year.
Skopbank, which had to be rescued by the Bank of Finland last year, has said
it will need additional financial support before the end of the year. KOP
has indicated it may have to seek support from the FM20bn state guarantee
fund early next year if losses continue at current levels.
Mr Vesa Vainio, Unitas chief executive said: 'High domestic interest rates
are the banking sector's most acute problem. Unless interest rates come
down, no increase in net income from financing operations, the banks' major
source of income, will be possible.'
Mr Jorma Aranko, director-general of the Finnish banking supervision
authority, suggested the state may convert financial support into majority
stakes.
Details, Page 28
