<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / French threat to farm reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE has no intention of complying with agreed reforms to the Common
Agriculture Policy (CAP), senior European Commission officials said in
Brussels yesterday.
Since France is Europe's main farming superpower, and its leading farm
exporter, this may put in jeopardy principal aims of the reform, including
substantial cuts to the farm subsidy regime that is hobbling the EC budget.
It would also explain France's increasingly fierce opposition to a
compromise settlement on the Uruguay Round of talks on world trade
liberalisation, raising fresh doubts about whether a deal can be reached.
Optimism among Community negotiators that they are able to conclude a deal
with the US is underpinned by an assumption that the CAP reforms agreed in
May will deliver the farm subsidy cuts demanded by the US and other farm
exporters.
Hopes have risen this week that a breakthrough is imminent in the
long-stalled Uruguay Round negotiations, following US-EC talks in Brussels
early this week, which reached tentative agreement on two of three
unresolved disputes over subsidised farm trade.
Negotiators failed to settle the last outstanding issue, on the EC's oilseed
subsidy regime, because the US could not be convinced that proposed CAP
reforms would deliver the cuts that EC officials say would follow.
During talks aimed at persuading intransigent French officials that a Gatt
deal can be agreed without adding to reforms already worked out under the
CAP reform, senior European Commission officials have told the French that
even if the EC accepts the full 24 per cent cut in subsidised cereals
exports the US wants, the Community will still be able to export 23.5m
tonnes in six years' time.
This would be more than the 19m tonnes of exports projected under the reform
of the CAP.
But French officials told them they do not believe the CAP reform will work
or be adhered to. 'It is clear now that France never really intended to
comply with CAP reform,' one senior Commission official declared yesterday.
If Washington now concludes that France, the US's main competitor, thinks
the CAP reform which underpins the Gatt negotiations is not to be taken
seriously, their last-ditch efforts to obtain a deal may evaporate. The
danger of a trade war between the US and the EC would then be grave, with
the entire international trading system likely to be affected.
The French position ignores inconvenient facts, EC officials say:
it is the US, which originally wanted 90 per cent cuts on export subsidies
and 75 per cent cuts on internal support, that has moved towards the EC
negotiating position, which most Community officials see as strengthened by
President Bush's electoral plight.
Quite apart from France's commitments under CAP reform, President
Mitterrand, UK prime minister John Major and Mr Delors all agreed at July's
Munich summit of the Group of Seven on a 21 per cent cut in subsidised food
exports, according to member-state and Commission officials.
The 24 per cent cut sought by Gatt and the US was originally put forward by
Mr Ruud Lubbers, Dutch prime minister and then EC president, at a meeting in
The Hague last November with Mr Bush.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
