<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
So far the BBC's social affairs series Public Eye has caused remarkably
little excitement. Perhaps today's programme, the first in a fresh series,
will change that. Called 'The Mad Cow Contagion', it is concerned with BSE,
an epidemic it says has become far more widespread than was ever predicted,
and which has now crossed into a number of other species (8.00 BBC2).
That is followed (8.30) by Royal Gardens, a series presented by Sir Roy
Strong who seems to be teetering on the brink of Crazed Pundit Syndrome: the
condition in which people such as Magnus Pike and David Bellamy cease to be
primarily presenters and become, instead, the arm-waving subjects of their
programmes. Strong already looks a bit like the chap with mutton-chop
whiskers who talks in tic-tac, and it would be no surprise to find him
describing Kew and Frogmore via semaphore.
The best new police series for years is Between The Lines, BBC1's drama
about an internal investigation unit. In today's episode a demonstration
turns into a riot but the investigators find themselves hampered by a police
commander (9.30).
</TEXT>
