   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LOTUS Development, the US personal computer software company, reported a 6
per cent decline in third-quarter revenues as it lost ground in the market
for programs that run on PCs using the popular Microsoft Windows program.
A pre-tax gain of Dollars 34.6m from the sale of stock in Sybase, another
software company, brought net income for the quarter to Dollars 30.1m, or 72
cents a share, compared with earnings of Dollars 21.5m, or 48 cents, in last
year's third-quarter.
Revenue was Dollars 206.7m, down from Dollars 218.8m last year.
Without the gain from the sale of Sybase stock, earnings totalled Dollars
7.3m, or 17 cents.
'Seasonal softness and recessions in key international economies, along with
continued price competition, contributed to the quarter's modest decline in
revenue,' said Mr Ed Gillis, chief financial officer.
'We anticipate that certain of these factors will continue to affect our
business in the near term.'
Large initial shipments in the third quarter of 1991 of 1-2-3 for Windows, a
version of Lotus' spreadsheet program, resulted in negative year-to-year
comparisons, he added.
Competition from Microsoft has significantly reduced Lotus' share of the
spreadsheet market. Lotus has, however achieved a leadership position in the
emerging 'workgroup' computer software market.
'Over the next several quarters, we expect to increase our overall share of
Windows desktops, based on the strength of our offerings across the major
Windows application categories,' Mr Gillis added.
Nine-month net income rose 76 per cent to Dollars 65.8m, or Dollars 1.52 a
share, from Dollars 37.3m or 84 cents. Revenue rose 13 per cent to Dollars
654.1m, from Dollars 579.7m.
