<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / International Company News: Philip Morris shares fall on
lower US tobacco sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Philip Morris, which earlier this week won control of
Scandinavia's Freia Marabou in a Dollars 1.5bn bid, fell yesterday after the
tobacco and food company reported a small decline in domestic cigarette
shipments in the third quarter, and predicted a much larger fall in the
final three months.
By lunchtime, the shares were down Dollars 4 1/4 at Dollars 79 3/4 .
Overall, the company - one of the nation's most reliable profit generators -
posted a 16.4 per cent rise in net income, at Dollars 1.29bn, for the third
quarter.
The advance, which came on a 9 per cent sales increase, translated into a 20
per cent rise in earnings per share, to Dollars 1.44. Philip Morris said it
still expected to post a 20 per cent increase in full-year earnings per
share.
But the third quarter threw up a significantly smaller, 10.5 per cent
increase in operating profits, at Dollars 2.81bn. This reflected strong
advances from the international tobacco and food divisions, single-digit
profits growth in the domestic tobacco and food operations, and declining
profits at the Miller Brewing Company subsidiary, the nation's
second-largest beer manufacturer.
In the big domestic tobacco business - which accounts for almost half of
operating profits - the company saw cigarette shipments fall by 0.5 per cent
to 53bn units, although sales, in value terms, were up by 5.4 per cent at
Dollars 2.97bn, and operating profits 8.5 per cent higher at Dollars 1.3bn.
Morris warned that the trend would continue.
Results from the brewing business were also disappointing, with operating
profits falling from Dollars 94m to Dollars 55m on sales of Dollars 1.04bn
(down from Dollars 1.13bn).
By contrast, the international tobacco business pushed up operating profits
from Dollars 497m to Dollars 589m, and the international food side saw a
rise from Dollars 209m to Dollars 277m.
The results leave Philip Morris posting after-tax profits of Dollars 3.74bn
(up from Dollars 2.24bn) on sales of Dollars 44.2bn (up from Dollars 42.8bn)
for the first nine months.
</TEXT>
