<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Labour sees threat to hospital jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JOB LOSSES among health service workers in London resulting from hospital
closures could reach unacceptable levels, Mr David Blunkett, Labour's shadow
health secretary, warned yesterday.
He called on Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, to produce a
coherent strategy for all sectors of healthcare in the capital before the
implementation of any closures arising from the Tomlinson report.
The report on health provision in London, by Sir Bernard Tomlinson, former
chairman of the Northern Regional Health Authority, is expected shortly.
Mr Blunkett said: 'In essence, we are trying to avoid happening to London
healthcare and London health workers what is happening this week to the
mining industry and the miners.' He insisted that Labour's support for any
closures was conditional on remedies for the 'scandal' of current
inadequacies in community and primary care.
'Tomlinson must not be used to bring about cuts in funding and the switch of
resources to meet the government's pledges for the coming year in other
parts of the country,' Mr Blunkett said.
Conditions in the 'agenda for change' which the government would have to
fulfil to secure Labour support for any closures included:
No changes before the pressure on acute services and the action needed to
cut London's waiting lists is assessed.
An agreed strategy for replacement facilities. A London regional health
authority to be established. All decisions on individual hospitals to be
based on health needs rather than site value.
</TEXT>
