<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / North West challenges Ofwat on price increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTH WEST WATER was the only water and sewerage company to challenge by
last night's deadline the request of Ofwat, the water industry regulator, to
hold back next spring's price rises.
North West said it had issued a counter-notice - a formal appeal - to
Ofwat's statement two weeks ago that if it held back prices as much as Ofwat
had asked it would not be able to afford to clean up the Mersey as required
by new environmental rules.
Two weeks ago Ofwat told the 10 large water and sewerage companies and nine
of the 22 smaller water-only companies that they should hold back next
spring's price rises by an average of 2 percentage points.
Their licences allow prices to rise each year by the rate of inflation plus
a 'K' factor, but Ofwat has argued that construction costs have been lower
than expected because of the recession, and that the benefits should reach
consumers. It gave the companies until midnight last night to respond.
Mr Clive Elphick, North West's general manager for economic regulation,
said: 'We have had to spend Pounds 430m more than planned - an extra year's
spending - between 1989 and 1994.'
Thames, Severn Trent, Anglian, Northumbrian, Wessex and Yorkshire have not
issued counter-notices. They have, however, persuaded Ofwat in the past two
weeks that they should hold back prices by between 0.4 per cent and 1 per
cent, less than half the level that Ofwat originally requested. Of those,
Anglian, Thames, Northumbrian and Yorkshire have struck two-year deals with
Ofwat, so they will avoid further changes before Ofwat's wide-ranging review
of the industry pricing structure in 1994.
Southern Water is the only company to have agreed a higher 'K' with Ofwat.
Its prices will rise next spring by inflation plus 3.9 per cent, against 3.5
per cent last year.
Mr Graham Hawker, managing director of Welsh Water, said: 'We told our
customers in June that we would hold back prices by 1.5 per cent, and Ofwat
has agreed that, so we have not sent a counter-notice.' Last night South
West Water had not issued a counter-notice or completed discussions with
Ofwat.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
