<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / British Coal bidder pulls out of race: Customer's imports to
rise tenfold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANGLO UNITED, British Coal's second-largest customer after the electricity
generators, has withdrawn as a possible bidder for the nationalised industry
because the severity of the pit cuts has left the operation too small to be
of interest.
The company is also being forced to increase its annual coal imports from
100,000 tonnes to almost 1m tonnes because of the pit closures.
Mr David McErlain, chairman, said yesterday: 'Eighteen months ago we were
looking at a business with 30 mines selling 50m tonnes to the generators.
Now it is only 20 mines. It's suddenly a small industry and getting
smaller.'
Mr McErlain also said that executives from his company would visit Australia
and South Africa shortly to discuss purchases of coal.
Anglo United owns the Coalite smokeless fuel company and also distributes 3m
tonnes of coal a year. But many of the UK mines that supply the company are
on the shutdown list. British Coal will try to meet its needs, but there
will be a growing shortfall.
Mr McErlain blamed the growth of gas-fired power generation for the
shrinkage of coal, and urged that Professor Stephen Littlechild, the
electricity regulator, investigate it.
'I hope that the government will look at this and see that people are
worried about the viability, and get it looked into,' he said.
Mr Malcolm Edwards, the former commercial director of British Coal who left
after disagreements over the cuts, is to lead a consortium which will
attempt to lease four pits due for closure in South Yorkshire: Markham Main,
Hatfield, Bentley and Rossington.
Mr Edwards told BBC Leeds: 'Here we are dealing with mines, it has been said
over and over again, which are among the best in Europe.' He said he had
held talks with Brian Nichols Associates of New South Wales who would
operate the mines.
Mr Crispian Hotson, chief executive of Ryan Group, the UK's largest private
coal mining company, said he had put a proposal to Mr Eggar to break British
Coal into five competing companies, with two in the Midlands and one in each
of Wales, the north-east and Scotland. That would break up centralised
decision-making, he said, and increase efficiency.
'Selling it as a single entity or a fudged duopoly will never achieve the
right end. If the right amount of competition is introduced, British Coal
could be the envy of the industry.'
</TEXT>
