<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Eggar sets out sell-off dates: Minister sees 'long road' to
privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT will press ahead with plans to privatise British Coal in
spite of the mounting furore over the decision to close more than half of
its pits.
Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, said yesterday that he hoped to present
legislation late next month or by Christmas at the latest.
But he said there would be 'a long road' to privatisation, and he did not
expect the shape and form of the sale to be completed until next July at the
earliest.
Meanwhile, he said, 'no irrevocable decisions have been taken on issues of
concern to those involved in the privatisation'.
Mr Eggar, addressing an Institute of Energy conference, said that four
issues would be taken into account:
The safety and health of mineworkers in a newly privatised industry must be
paramount.
The reduced energy costs resulting from the cuts at British Coal must be
passed to consumers by the generators.
The mining and marketing of coal should be kept separate from the leasing
and licensing of exploration and production. There would be a new licensing
authority which would have no conflict of interest in awarding licences.
The pensions and concessionary fuel entitlements of past and present
employees must be safeguarded.
Mr Eggar also repeated a commitment to give management and staff the
opportunity to have a stake in the business. He stressed that no decisions
had yet been taken on whether there should be a trade sale, an issue of
shares or a management/employee buy-out.
