FT  16 OCT 92 / International Capital Markets: Glavunion notes issue blazes
trail for Czechs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GLAVUNION, a joint venture between a Czech glassmaker and Glaverbel of
Belgium, has issued the first medium-term corporate bonds in Czechoslovakia,
paving the way for the development of a new debt market in the country.
The bonds, worth Kcs200m (Dollars 7.3m) and maturing in 1998, have a coupon
of 13.5 per cent. They are expected to be traded on the interim secondary
market.
Credit Suisse First Boston in Prague, which lead-managed the issue, has
placed the bonds with a selection of non-bank financial institutions and
corporate investors.
So far, the secondary market has only intermittently traded state bonds and
debt issued by Komercni Banka and General Credit Bank, of Bratislava, two
leading commercial banks in the Czech and Slovak republics.
The Glavunion bond issue is also expected to be one of the first securities
listed on the Prague Stock Exchange, due to open this year.
The bonds will pave the way for other local corporate borrowers to raise
money domestically outside the bank market. Local enterprises have been
hard-pressed to find affordable funds to finance investment programmes as
commercial banks are unwilling to lend money for more than one year.
</TEXT>
