FT  16 OCT 92 / International Capital Markets: Pru chief issues plea for
greater treasury detail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEAD of one of the largest institutional investors in the UK stock
market has called for greater disclosure of corporate treasury policies in
companies' accounts.
Mr Hugh Jenkins, chief executive of Prudential Portfolio Managers, was
speaking at a conference hosted by the Association of Corporate Treasurers
in London earlier this week. Prudential Portfolio Managers has Pounds 21bn
of its Pounds 50bn of funds under management invested in the UK stock
market, accounting for 3.5 per cent of the market.
The ACT accepted a call from Mr Jenkins to 'establish a working party with
representatives of institutional shareholders in order to devise appropriate
levels of disclosure of corporate Treasury management activities for
publication in annual reports'.
The Association of British Insurers, the National Association of Pension
Funds and the Accounting Standards Board will be involved in setting up the
working party.
Mr Jenkins complained that, in the accounts of many of the largest listed
companies, reports on corporate treasury matters are 'minimal in most
cases', even though the Report and Accounts is the correct medium for such
disclosure.
Only a few UK companies, including RTZ and Courtaulds, describe their
Treasury activities, including interest rate and currency exposure
management policies, in any detail.
Mr Jenkins suggested that companies' audit committees should monitor systems
of risk control and ensure that internal control systems are adequate. He
also emphasised that a clear view of the strategic aims of the Treasury
function was vital.
Mr Jenkins added that corporate treasury departments should not be treated
as profit centres. 'Value can certainly be added, but treasurers should work
to facilitate their companies' core business activities,' he said.
</TEXT>
