FT  16 OCT 92 / International Company News: Semi-Tech shows rise of 210% in
first half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEMI-Tech (Global), the Hong Kong owner of the Singer sewing machine group,
announced net profits of HKDollars 704m (USDollars 91m) for the six months
ended July 1992, a 210 per cent increase on the comparable period of last
year.
Earnings were boosted by the HKDollars 526m exceptional profit from the sale
of 8m shares in New York-listed Singer. On a recurring and comparable basis
 -assuming the same percentage contribution from Singer - profits would have
risen 17 per cent.
Turnover increased to HKDollars 4.7bn from HKDollars 4.5bn. Its 51 per
cent-owned subsidiary, Singer, has successfully expanded its product range
from sewing machines into consumer durables, resulting in sales growth in
the majority of its markets.
Semi-Tech is starting to focus on mainland China for expansion. Singer has
formed a joint venture in Shanghai to manufacture sewing machines for the
local market, while its parent is setting up a retail network to distribute
its products in the world's largest consumer market.
The directors recommended an interim dividend of HKDollars 0.23, up from
HKDollars 0.20 in 1991.
