<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London COCOA rose sharply in early trade on news of an Ivorian decision to
ban purchases of mid-crop and sub-grade cocoa for the 1992-93 season. There
also appeared to be less prospect of the Ivory Coast selling cocoa around
current levels after its decision to keep its producer price for good cocoa
at 200 CFA francs a kg and a further fall in the value of sterling against
the French franc. News of a 9.2 per cent rise in the third-quarter Dutch
cocoa grind was seen as mildly supportive. GOLD was fixed little changed in
the afternoon from its four-week low morning fix on the London bullion
market. Trading was choppy after heavy Middle East selling. There seemed to
be one major player governing business after selling heavily into the
Australian market in early trade and then later into Europe, dealers said.
There were some producer sales; producers were unhappy to be selling, but
some needed to cover costs even though they were helping to drive the market
lower.
Compiled from Reuters
