<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Etam continues its recovery with Pounds
1.2m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ETAM, the fashion retailer in which a South African concern has acquired a
34 per cent stake, built on last year's turnround in first-half profits to
make Pounds 1.2m pre-tax.
The improvement, from Pounds 35,000, followed a 7 per cent turnover increase
to Pounds 105.8m (Pounds 98.5m) in the 28 weeks to August 15. The interim
dividend is being raised 10 per cent to 1.65p.
Etam caters for women and girls from five upwards in its eponymous stores,
Snob and Tammy Girl. Less than 4 per cent of sales come from men's wear. The
group traded from 238 (239) stores and reduced its floorspace by nearly 1
per cent.
Mr Keith Miles, finance director, said sales had improved across the women's
wear ranges. Men's wear continued to lose money, and a boys' wear range had
been brought in to complement Tammy Girl. Its share of the women's wear
market had improved from 1.4 per cent in 1986 to 3 per cent.
Cost control had continued to be a priority.
While like-for-like sales were ahead since the half-way stage, consumer
confidence had 'totally disappeared in the three weeks since black
Wednesday,' Mr Miles said.
A cut in net interest payments to Pounds 25,000 (Pounds 412,000) was partly
offset by increased charges of Pounds 461,000 (Pounds 128,000) for
withdrawing from loss-making shops.
After capital spending of Pounds 4.2m (Pounds 1.2m), borrowings stood at
Pounds 1.6m (Pounds 8.1m) and were expected to be eliminated by the
year-end.
After a high tax charge (is largely mitigated over the full year), earnings
per share stood at 0.52p (losses of 0.59p).
COMMENT
Etam, like Next, is well established on the recovery trail and this has been
fully reflected in the share price, which has soared above Oceana Investment
Corporation's 185p-a-share bid. The progress has been partly the product of
hard graft on costs and partly of the comparative resilience of the women's
wear market - so why bother with the Boyz 2 range? There is room to continue
marginal improvement - last year it was little more than 6 per cent at the
pre-interest level - but the task may become more difficult. Cost pressures
remain and a wage increase in the second half will make the staff line look
less flattering. Meanwhile sales at the 'Sharon' and 'Debbie' end of the
market might well be affected by rising unemployment, even if it is among
the menfolk. A full-year pre-tax profit forecast of Pounds 14.5m gives a
prospective p/e of 17 to 18 on yesterday's close of 243p. This looks fully
priced. It remains worth holding for genuine recovery, and Oceana's interest
limits the downside.
