<DATE>921016
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / UK Company News: European Leisure falls Pounds 45.6m into
the red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN LEISURE, the troubled disco and snooker hall operator which is
struggling to reorganise despite a mountain of debt, yesterday reported a
Pounds 45.6m full-year pre-tax loss after exceptional items.
The exceptional charges in the year to June 30 totalled Pounds 47.5m (Pounds
880,000) including Pounds 36.9m in provisions for losses expected on
disposals and Pounds 10.6m in goodwill transfers from reserves, and were
Pounds 610,000 higher than the charges announced at the time of the interim
results.
The full year pre-tax loss compares with a Pounds 5.23m profit and came on
turnover down 11.3 per cent to Pounds 75.1m (Pounds 84.8m) reflecting the
impact of the recession in the UK and continental Europe.
While reduced consumer spending has affected the leisure market as a whole,
high unemployment among young people has particularly hit European Leisure's
customer base.
This, coupled with intense competition, affected profitability, although the
group's snooker operations proved more resilient and its Maygay Machines
business, which designs and manufactures fruit machines, reported a
substantial increase in turnover and operating profits.
Overall trading profits fell by almost 27 per cent to Pounds 9.58m (Pounds
13.1m), but were helped by Pounds 2m of overhead savings and tighter
management controls. Net interest payments rose to Pounds 7.7m (Pounds
6.96m).
Losses per share were 29.04p (earnings of 2.52p).
As already announced there was a Pounds 8.81m (Pounds 7.35m) extraordinary
charge relating to the disposal of the group's two floating nightclubs on
the Tyne.
Mr Ian Rock, chief executive, said the group's substantial disposal
programme, which involves selling 30 out of 111 units including all of its
loss-making businesses in France and Spain, was making progress.
With shareholders' funds reduced to Pounds 33.8m (Pounds 76.2m) the group's
gearing has increased from 94 per cent to 227 per cent.
The group remains under investigation by the Serious Fraud Office concerning
its acquisition of Midsummer Leisure in 1990.
COMMENT
European Leisure ran into trouble soon after its acrimonious takeover of
Midsummer Leisure. Since then the new management team has written down
assets to more realistic levels and identified a fifth of its retail estate,
including the loss-making continental businesses, for disposal. However, the
recession has hit the group's core young customer group hard. This means
that trading profits only just cover the costs of servicing the group's
debt. Although the full-year result held no new nasty surprises, the
management faces a long uphill struggle to sell businesses and reduce debt -
a difficult task in the current climate. Until the balance sheet is
considerably strengthened there will be no shareholder dividends. In the
meantime the share price is bumping along the bottom at 3p. For those
unlucky enough to own the stock, it is probably not worth selling.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-13291</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJPBWAB5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921016
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Pentland criticised as talks fail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PENTLAND'S DECISION to call off negotiations with Bernard Tapie Finance
(BTF) over the purchase of Adidas, the sports shoe company, led to a
characteristically fiery attack from Mr Tapie, and a characteristically
reserved response from Pentland.
Mr Tapie accused Pentland of trying to renegotiate the price of the
purchase, agreed in July, while Pentland said it had found problems which
BTF had been unable to resolve. Because of a confidentiality agreement,
Pentland and its advisers refused to comment on what problems they had
unearthed.
But behind the recriminations must lie a profound sense of disappointment on
all sides that a deal with remarkable internal logic and cohesion appears to
be off.
Pentland, with net cash of more than Pounds 250m from the sale of a stake in
Reebok, US sports shoe maker, wanted another international brand to nurture.
Adidas had the brand but needed new investment to revive it. Mr Tapie needed
the money to restore his business empire, which has been in decline since he
bought Adidas in a highly leveraged deal in 1990.
Mr Frank Farrant, Pentland finance director, said the company's outstanding
20 per cent stake in Adidas, acquired last year, would be retained even
though a new agreement with Mr Tapie was unlikely, especially given the
ferocity of his attacks on Pentland yesterday. 'From our point of view the
deal is now dead,' Mr Farrant said.
This leaves Adidas with the same problems which have constrained its growth
since Mr Tapie's takeover, a lack of cash.
BTF said yesterday it would invest 'between FFr500m and FFr600m (Pounds 60m
to Pounds 70m)' in Adidas and discuss with other minority shareholders, a
group dominated by Credit Lyonnais and Banque Worms, the French banks, and
the Assurances Generales de France insurance group.
Mr Tapie said they needed 'to discuss ways of saving Adidas as quickly as
possible'. It has had serious financial problems and is on course for
another year of losses.
However it is not clear whether BTF would be able to finance its share of
such a capital injection. Mr Tapie has in the past made unfulfilled promises
to provide capital for Adidas. Even if the investment is made, it will not
be enough to solve Adidas' problems.
It has been slow to take advantage of cheaper production in the Far East,
and its margins are about 1.5 per cent compared nearly 15 for rivals Nike
and Reebok. It has an inadequate share, about 2 per cent, of the world's
largest sports shoe market in the US, and its brand name needs reviving in
other major markets.
'It is potentially a great brand,' an industry observer said. 'But the
costs, financial and political, of closing factories in Europe will be very
high. And the days of premium branding and ridiculous prices for sports
shoes seem to be over,' he said.
Adidas' future is further complicated because at least some clauses of an
exclusivity agreement between BTF and Pentland remain in place. This would
appear to guarantee Pentland some first refusal over any sales of Adidas
shares, and could frustrate attempts by Mr Tapie to sell the company to a
third party.
Pentland's future is equally uncertain, although the company's cash pile
allows it time to consider its options. It has a collection of smaller brand
names, like swimwear group Speedo, which it is developing.
But the company's ambitions to manage a major brand have been frustrated
again. Analysts confessed to a sense of deja vu. Pentland tried in 1988 to
take over Parker, the pen maker, but pulled out when certain environmental
indemnities were not forthcoming.
According to BTF's advisers, the conservatism and caution of Mr Stephen
Rubin, Pentland chairman, helped scupper the deal because he kept insisting
on more and more guarantees. Pentland's advisers claimed that Pentland had
to be cautious because of the nature and complexity of Mr Tapie's group.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-13292</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJPBWAB4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921016
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Owen &amp; Robinson shows heavier loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OWEN &amp; ROBINSON, the jewellery and sports footwear retailer which brought in
new management in April, yesterday announced doubled pre-tax losses of
Pounds 2.44m for the half-year to July 31.
Both the preferred and the ordinary dividend (0.15p) are being passed.
The deepening losses from last time's Pounds 1.23m were struck on turnover
up 29 per cent at Pounds 10.2m (Pounds 7.9m). The 16 per cent sales rise in
Gold Centre, which increased the number of its shops by 22 to 59 during
1991, was entirely accounted for by those new shops, the company said.
Like-for-like sales, however, were down.
Foothold, which lifted the number of its sports footwear shops by 5 to 13 in
1991, lifted sales 66 per cent, though on a like-for-like basis sales only
rose 10 per cent.
The new management team started the group rationalisaimmediately - some 110
posts, or 25 per cent of the workforce, had been lost. The savings from this
and the other cost reduction schemes would come through in the second half,
Mr Smith said.
Operating losses were Pounds 1.73m (Pounds 450,000) and, though interest
payable was down at Pounds 405,000 (Pounds 778,000) on borrowings of Pounds
6.1m, there were exceptional costs of Pounds 300,000 relating to the
departure of senior management. Mr Smith said gearing was 'awful'. Losses
per share emerged at 5.7p (7.8p) reflecting the full effect of the 1991
rights issue.
</TEXT>
