</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Bush battles to close poll gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush, struggling to regain ground in the last 19 days of
the US presidential campaign, last night strongly defended his trade policy
and decried those who favour protectionism.
'Free and fair trade is the answer, not protectionism. We've had tough
economic times and it's exports that have saved us,' Mr Bush said in the
second of three televised debates with Mr Bill Clinton, his Democratic
challenger, and Mr Ross Perot, the independent candidate.
Answering the same question, Mr Clinton said he favoured more trade but on
fair terms. 'The trick is to expand our export base and expand our trade on
terms that are fair to us,' he added.
Perched uncomfortably on high stools, the three candidates fielded questions
from an audience of 209 uncommitted voters in Richmond, Virginia.
Although Mr Bush briefly embarked on an attack on Mr Clinton's character and
student opposition to the Vietnam war, the audience quickly made clear it
was unhappy with the mudslinging in the campaign for the November 3
election.
Mr Perot attacked the North American Free Trade Agreement (Nafta) recently
negotiated by President Bush with Mexico and Canada, warning that it would
open the way for many businesses to transfer jobs to Mexico.
'There will be a giant sucking sound going south,' he said.
But Mr Bush said that exports had saved the US during the current global
economic slowdown, and said Nafta would not mean job losses to Mexico.
The debate came as latest opinion polls showed Mr Clinton still well ahead
of Mr Bush and Mr Perot. A CNN/USA Today poll gave Mr Clinton a 15-point
lead over the president, based on voter surveys conducted in the three days
after Sunday's first presidential debate. It showed Mr Clinton with 47 per
cent support to 32 per cent for Mr Bush and 15 per cent for Mr Perot.
But another poll, by ABC News, showed that Mr Bush might at last be starting
to cut into Mr Clinton's lead, because it showed the Democratic challenger
just seven points ahead. The poll, conducted on Tuesday and Wednesday, gave
Mr Clinton 44 per cent of the vote to 37 per cent for Mr Bush and 11 per
cent for Mr Perot.
Race for the White House, Pages 8 and 9
Green spirit of America, Page 22
