<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / BR fares to rise by up to 9.5%: Increases in rail and London
Transport prices prompt protests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL and London Transport prompted angry protests yesterday by
announcing government-approved fare rises averaging 7.5 per cent and 8.5 per
cent respectively, more than double the rate of inflation.
The increases come as private sector businesses are moderating or foregoing
price rises in the face of a severe recession. But BR and LT are able to
impose big increases because many of their passengers, particularly
rush-hour commuters in London and the south-east, cannot realistically turn
to alternative means of transport.
Network SouthEast commuters will pay up to 9.5 per cent more for season
tickets, while holders of LT Travelcard season tickets will pay up to 10 per
cent more.
Other rail travellers will face lower-than-average increases because BR is
trying to stem the downturn in leisure travel by keeping off-peak fares
competitive.
The Central Transport Consultative Committee, the statutory rail passengers'
watchdog, accused BR of exploiting its monopoly position.
Major-General Lennox Napier, the committee's chairman, said: 'Fare increases
above the rate of inflation are only justifiable where there have been
material improvements in services and where quality standards are being
fully met.
'Both InterCity and Network SouthEast failed to meet some of their key
quality targets in 1991-92, so the decision to raise season ticket rates by
an average of twice the rate of inflation is unreasonable.'
Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, said: 'Britain's railways are
now the most expensive and least invested, with reducing quality, of any
developed European railway system.'
British Rail said higher fares were needed to offset a downturn in revenues.
It was also facing higher safety and security costs and needed to fund a
substantial investment programme.
It said the highest fare increases were being paid by commuters who had
benefited from new trains.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said: 'Both BR and London
Underground are in the middle of enormous investment programmes. Much of
that money comes from the taxpayer, but it is only right that passengers
should make a contribution.'
